Anonymous Tue 11 Aug 2020 23:48:25 No.32069370 Report
Quoted By: >>32069595
>>32069072
The best way to do it depends on the source, but for pastebin I'd use the raw.
file ID's the wget'ed download as
xxxxxxxx: ASCII text, with very long lines, with CRLF line terminators
Really, this is bash 101.
A good biut of things depend on how you organize your flat file. One option is wget the pastebin to /tmp, compare it to the on disk copy, mv the newly downloaded file from /tmp if larger, and use awk/sed to replace relevant entries in the flat file.
Can you accomplish this with a higher level language? Certainly.
My point is you start from
$ wget https://pastebin.com/raw/$STORY
and build what fits your sorting system.
No reason you can't use Excel to make a tab delimited file and run cron on a Windows system via services or WSL.

Anonymous Wed 12 Aug 2020 01:13:33 No.32071171 Report
Quoted By: >>32071237
>>32069595
I'm rather drunk, so this is skeletal

#!/bin/bash
oldsize=`ls -l $ARCHIVE/$1 | awk '{ print $5 }'`
cd /tmp
wget https://pastebin.com/raw/$1
newsize=`ls -l /tmp/$1 | awk '{ print $5 }'`
if (( $newsize >= $oldsize)); then echo UPDATED
cp -dpR /tmp/$1 $ARCHIVE/$1
else
echo Writefags are lazy
fi
rm /tmp/$1

define ARCHIVE prior to oldsize
this will pull a single single pastebin called after the script, like
$ pbupdate XXXXXXXX
where XXXXXXXX = the alphanumeric code for the pastebin

how I'd deal with a flat file is drop the index, in this case the pastebin code from above as the first field, make the second field the story name, make the third field the current file size (thus we could pull $oldsize from the current line), and make the fourth field the last updated date

If you're scared of using mv, use cp -dpR

So essentially I'd call a cron job, that calls a script whose only purpose is to iterate through a flat file and call a second script (the rough code I included here)

I'd suggest reading through the bash scripting faq if you're interested. bash is rarely the fastest tool, but unless you've dropped to an emergency shell it's near ubiquitous.

As anyone that's toyed with bash can tell you, I've left more out than provided.
One way to avoid a mv ./ /$target` is to always define the $SOURCE. Since that should be coming from a flat file in the automated, line by line script, and have an appropriate if/else statement, you're rather safe.

I suggest stepping through faqs and their examples. Once you get the basics of bash, i recommend the basics of sed and awk.
After that, look at whatever scripting language fits your needs.
